{"title":"Unicoder-VL: A Universal Encoder for Vision and Language by Cross-modal Pre-training","domain":"MULTIMODAL","seeds":[{"problem":"Existing CV and NLP pretraining fail to jointly model fine-grained interactions between image regions and long natural-language sequences, limiting performance on cross-modal tasks like retrieval and visual commonsense reasoning.","method":"Unicoder-VL is a single-stream multi-layer Transformer (initialized from BERT) that ingests wordpieces together with region-level visual features and 5-D box geometry from a frozen Faster R-CNN (top-100 RoIs), projecting visual and location features into a shared space with layer normalization. It is cross-modally pre-trained on 3.8M image–caption pairs with three tasks: (i) Masked Language Modeling masking 15% of words and predicting them conditioned on all image regions; (ii) Masked Object Classification masking 15% of regions (90% replaced with zero vectors) and predicting detector-derived object labels from cross-modal context; (iii) Visual–Linguistic Matching using the [CLS] representation to classify matched vs. mismatched pairs with both negative-image and negative-caption sampling. This yields context-aware, aligned token and region embeddings that fuse vision and language early."},{"problem":"Turning a pre-trained cross-modal encoder into a strong image–text retrieval model and assessing generalization without task-specific supervision.","method":"For retrieval, Unicoder-VL scores image–text pairs via a learned similarity s(w,v) from the [CLS]-based cross-modal representation and is fine-tuned with a hardest-negative triplet loss in both directions (image-to-text, text-to-image), sampling three negatives per positive. This delivers new state-of-the-art results on MSCOCO and Flickr30k (e.g., Flickr30k R@1: 86.2% sentence, 71.5% image), substantially outperforming prior methods. For zero-shot retrieval, it directly reuses the pre-trained VLM classifier as the matching score without fine-tuning, achieving competitive R@K (e.g., MSCOCO 1K R@1: 54.4% sentence, 43.4% image; Flickr30k R@1: 64.3% sentence, 48.4% image), indicating the learned alignment generalizes beyond the pretraining data."}]}
